text: "Mechanism of action of botulinum toxin is:",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Inhibits NM receptor", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Inhibits reuptake of acetyl choline", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Inhibits release of acetylcholine from lower motor neurons", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Inhibits synthesis of acetyl choline", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Botulinum toxin blocks neuromuscular transmission by inhibiting the release of acetylcholine (ACh) at the presynaptic terminals of lower motor neurons.<br><br>Mechanism:<br><br>* Botulinum toxin cleaves SNARE proteins (e.g., synaptobrevin, SNAP-25).\n* These proteins are essential for fusion of synaptic vesicles with the presynaptic membrane.\n* Their inhibition prevents exocytosis of acetylcholine, leading to failure of neuromuscular transmission.<br><br>Clinical correlation:<br><br>* Causes descending flaccid paralysis (e.g., botulism)\n* Used therapeutically in conditions like dystonia, spasticity, and cosmetic procedures<br><br>Why other options are incorrect:<br><br>* Inhibits NM receptor: Seen with drugs like curare, not botulinum toxin.\n* Inhibits reuptake of acetylcholine: ACh is not reuptaken like monoamines; it is degraded by acetylcholinesterase.\n* Inhibits synthesis of acetylcholine: Not the mechanism of botulinum toxin.",
images: []
