category: "Biochemistry",
subcategory: "01-basics-of-metabolism",
tags: ["PYQ", "NEET PG 2024"],
text: "A diabetic patient was advised exercise by the treating physician. The glucose transporter which is insulin sensitive is:",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Glut 1", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Glut 2", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Glut 3", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Glut 4", "is_correct": true}],
explanation: "GLUT-4 is the insulin-sensitive glucose transporter, primarily found in:<br><br>* Skeletal muscle\n* Adipose tissue<br><br>Mechanism:<br><br>* In response to insulin, GLUT-4 translocates from intracellular vesicles to the cell membrane\n* This increases glucose uptake into cells\n* Exercise can also stimulate GLUT-4 translocation independent of insulin<br><br>Clinical relevance in diabetes:<br><br>* Exercise improves glucose uptake even when insulin action is impaired\n* Hence, exercise is beneficial in diabetes management<br><br>Why other options are incorrect:<br><br>* GLUT-1: RBCs, brain (insulin-independent)\n* GLUT-2: Liver, pancreas (high Km, bidirectional)\n* GLUT-3: Neurons (high affinity, insulin-independent)",
